    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Passage indexing</strong> is a Google technology that evaluates individual sections of a web page independently, not just the page as a whole. Announced in October 2020 and rolled out in February 2021, it allows Google to rank a specific 150–200-word section for a precise query even when the surrounding page covers many different topics.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Launched</div>
            <div class="tms-value">February 2021</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Queries affected</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~7% of searches</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Before passage indexing, a 3,000-word guide containing one highly relevant 150-word section might not rank for a specific query because the rest of the page diluted the relevance signal. Passage indexing changed that — now the section itself can rank, regardless of what the rest of the page covers.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is passage indexing?</h2>
        <p>Passage indexing — Google calls it "passage ranking" internally — is the system Google uses to assess relevance at the sub-page level. Google still indexes entire pages. What changed in February 2021 is that the ranking algorithm can assign passage-level relevance scores to specific sections and use those scores when matching queries.</p>
        <p>The practical result: a comprehensive guide on gardening that includes a focused 200-word section on aphid prevention can now rank for "how to prevent aphids on tomato plants" — even though the page is not primarily about aphids. Before passage indexing, that section was too buried to surface.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's announcement</div>
          <p>Google's Search On 2020 event (October 2020) announced passage ranking as one of the biggest improvements in search relevance. Google stated the update would affect approximately <strong>7% of search queries across all languages</strong> at full rollout.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why passage indexing matters for content strategy</h2>
        <p>Passage indexing changes the ROI math for long-form content in three concrete ways:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Comprehensive guides become multi-query assets.</strong> A single 5,000-word pillar page can now rank for dozens of passage-level queries that previously required separate pages. One well-structured guide replaces ten thin pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Structure signals become ranking signals.</strong> Clear H2 and H3 headings, focused paragraphs, and distinct sections are no longer just UX choices — they are signals Google uses to identify and extract passages. Poorly structured pages leave passage-level opportunities on the table.</li>
          <li><strong>Long-tail queries become easier to win.</strong> Specific, low-volume queries (the ones that convert best) often find their answer buried in a comprehensive guide. Passage indexing surfaces those answers without requiring a dedicated page for each query.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How passage indexing works</h2>
        <p>Google's passage ranking system operates in four steps when processing a page:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Topic identification.</strong> Google identifies the overall topic of the page using page-level signals — title, H1, meta description, overall content.</li>
          <li><strong>Passage segmentation.</strong> Using BERT-based natural language processing, Google segments the page into topical passages, typically bounded by heading tags, paragraph breaks, and topic shifts.</li>
          <li><strong>Relevance scoring per passage.</strong> Each passage receives an independent relevance score for different query types. A passage explaining "how to fix aphid infestations" scores highly for that specific query, regardless of what score the overall page receives.</li>
          <li><strong>Query matching.</strong> When a user searches, Google matches the query against both page-level and passage-level signals. If a passage scores higher than any dedicated page, it can surface that page in results.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">BERT's role</div>
          <p>Passage ranking relies on BERT (Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers), Google's NLP model. BERT understands context and intent, so it can recognize when a passage answers a query even when the exact query words don't appear in the passage.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="types">Passage indexing vs. featured snippets — what is the difference?</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Passage Indexing</th><th>Featured Snippet</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>What it is</strong></td>
                <td>Ranking mechanism</td>
                <td>Display format</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>What it does</strong></td>
                <td>Determines which pages appear in results based on passage relevance</td>
                <td>Extracts a short answer to display above organic results</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Visible to user?</strong></td>
                <td>No — affects rank only</td>
                <td>Yes — shown above position 1</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Can they overlap?</strong></td>
                <td colspan="2">Yes — a passage that ranks well via passage indexing can also be pulled as a featured snippet</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Optimization</strong></td>
                <td>Clear structure, focused paragraphs, descriptive headings</td>
                <td>40-60 word direct answers after question headings</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real passage indexing examples</h2>
        <p>Here is how passage indexing creates value in practice:</p>

        <h3>1. The gardening guide</h3>
        <p>A site publishes a "Complete Guide to Vegetable Gardening" — a 4,500-word page covering soil prep, watering, fertilizing, pest control, and harvesting. Section 4 covers aphid prevention in 180 focused words with a clear H3 heading: "How to Prevent Aphids on Tomato Plants." With passage indexing, that section ranks for the specific query even though the page is not primarily about aphids.</p>

        <h3>2. The legal guide</h3>
        <p>A law firm publishes a 3,800-word LLC formation guide. Section 7 covers tax treatment for LLCs in 220 words with a descriptive H2. Before passage indexing, the page rarely ranked for "LLC tax treatment vs S-corp." After the update, section 7 began capturing traffic for that query — 18 different ranking positions from a single guide.</p>

        <h3>3. The HVAC maintenance guide</h3>
        <p>An HVAC company publishes an AC maintenance guide. The section on "how often to change AC filters" contains a direct answer in the first sentence, followed by a table of filter types and frequencies. Passage indexing surfaced that section for filter-change queries, generating leads from people who never read the full guide.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Passage indexing vs. topic clusters — which approach wins?</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use passage indexing (comprehensive guides)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You want one authoritative URL to own a topic</li>
              <li>Your audience reads in-depth before deciding</li>
              <li>You want multiple ranking opportunities from one content piece</li>
              <li>Your domain authority is moderate — fewer, stronger pages beat many thin ones</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use topic clusters (dedicated pages)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Each subtopic has significant standalone search volume</li>
              <li>You need separate landing pages for conversion tracking</li>
              <li>Different buyer personas need different entry points</li>
              <li>You have domain authority to support many indexed URLs</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">5 best practices to optimize for passage indexing</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Use descriptive H2 and H3 headings.</strong> Each heading should clearly describe what the section covers. "How to Prevent Aphids on Tomato Plants" outperforms "Pest Control" as a heading — it matches the specific queries you want the passage to rank for.</li>
          <li><strong>Write focused paragraphs, one idea each.</strong> Each paragraph should cover exactly one point. Multi-topic paragraphs confuse passage boundaries and dilute relevance scores.</li>
          <li><strong>Answer questions directly in the first sentence.</strong> When a section addresses a specific question, give the direct answer in the first sentence, then expand. Google extracts the opening of a passage most reliably.</li>
          <li><strong>Add FAQ sections to long guides.</strong> FAQ sections create highly focused passages — one question, one concise answer — that are naturally optimized for passage-level ranking and featured snippet extraction.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritize depth over quantity.</strong> A single 2,500-word guide with 10 distinct, well-structured sections creates 10 passage-level ranking opportunities. Ten 250-word thin pages create 10 pages that struggle to rank for anything.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — creating thin separate pages</div>
          <p>The instinct is to write a separate page for every subtopic. Passage indexing inverts this logic. A comprehensive guide with 10 well-structured sections can rank for all 10 subtopics from one URL, building topical authority faster than 10 thin pages competing with each other.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common passage indexing mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Vague headings</strong> — "More Information" or "Additional Tips" give Google no signal about what the passage covers.</li>
          <li><strong>Meandering paragraphs</strong> — covering multiple unrelated points in one paragraph makes it impossible for Google to assign a clean relevance score.</li>
          <li><strong>Missing direct answers</strong> — burying the answer three sentences into a paragraph reduces the likelihood of passage extraction.</li>
          <li><strong>Over-optimizing for passage ranking at the expense of coherence</strong> — pages should read naturally for humans first. Forced keyword insertion into headings hurts both UX and BERT's understanding.</li>
          <li><strong>Confusing passage indexing with featured snippets</strong> — optimizing for featured snippets (40-60 word direct answers) is complementary to passage indexing but is a different goal.</li>
        </ul>

